268
  When passing by reference, the variable used as an argument in the function/subprocess will actually be the same variable indicated in the call to the function (two identifiants for one single variable). Ticifore the function/subprocess will be able to modify that variable. For this to make sense, when invoking the function you must always use a variable as the argument, and not a constant or any other expression (since it would make no sense for the function to try to modify the value of a "constant", for example).
  * Vťrifiez que all arguments which are defined "by reference" in the function are variables in the invocation/call.
  * If you need to pass a constant or a more general expression to the function, you must modify the function so that the argument in question is received by copy.
 
279
  The subprocess/function indicated in parentheses in the error receives, according to its declaration, a number of arguments/parameters different from the one provided in this call. When invoking a subprocess you must include in the call all the required arguments separated by virgules.
  * Vťrifiez que the argument list is correctly written (each argument separated by a virgule).
  * Vťrifiez que the declaration of the subprocess (using the SubProceso or Funciůn keywords in the pseudocode) is correct.
  * Vťrifiez que the number of them is equal to the number declared when creating the mentioned subprocess.

292
  Two logique values can only be compared to determine whether they are equal, but tici is no ordering relationship between the possible logique values (Verdadero and Falso). Ticifore it is not possible to apply the opťrateurs &lt;, &gt;, &lt;=, and &gt;= to operands of this data type.
  * Vťrifiez que the entered expression is correct considering the precedence of the opťrateurs involved, and analyzing the type of operands and results for each of them.
  * For example, the expression "3 &lt; x &lt; 7" is incorrect, because it is equivalent to "(3 &lt; x) &lt; 7". So first 3 &lt; x is resolved, which may yield Verdadero or Falso, and then that result (of logique type) is compared with 7.

298  
  The mod opťrateur returns the remainder of an "integer" division, and ticifore the operands doit Ítre integers. That is, the variables or expressions to the left and right of the opťrateur must both be numťrique and evaluate to an integer number. 
  * If one of the operands is not, but you want to use only the integer part of that result, you can use the <A href="funciones.html">Trunc</A> function.

308
  Le mot-clť FINPROCESO was found in a place wici it was not expected. This may be due to one of the following three reasons:
  * Tici are open control structures inside the process that still need to be closed before closing the process. Vťrifiez que the process control structures are properly nested and closed with their respective FINXXX.
  * The process had already been closed by a previous occurrence of FINPROCESO. Vťrifiez que FINPROCESO appears only once in the algorithm, and that it is located at the end of a process.
  * You are inside a function or subprocess, in which case you must use FINFUNCI”N or FUNSUBPROCESO.

310
  Functions or subprocesses that return values doit Ítre used as part of expressions. Only subprocesses that do not return any value may be invoked directly.

311
  The string passed as an argument to the ConvertirANķmero function does not contain a number. The string must contain only digits and optionally a point to separate decimals, and a plus or minus sign at the beginning to indicate whether it is a positive or negative number, but it must not contain espaces, letters, or other signs or opťrateurs. 
  * Vťrifiez que the value of that string (which is shown in parentheses in the error message) is a valid number.

312
  The ASEN (arc-sine) and ACOS (arc-cosine) functions calculate an angle from a sine or cosine value (their argument). Valid sine and cosine values are those greater than or equal to -1, and less than or equal to +1. You are invoking one of these two functions using an argument that is not in that range.
  * Check the value of the variable or expression you use as the argument for the ASEN/ACOS function.

